			>
			<DIV></DIV>n public chat<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Sharbreena wrote:<BR>
<DIV>Jazzy is right though, in that there are some high end raiders who really do tend to "lord it" over casual's. While I may show off a little somtimes I generally don't have the time to farm those spots, I have maybe 10 hours a week&nbsp;I can devote to xp the rest is raiding. So for me I am out there to get as much aa or trial progression done as I can, not farm out wos.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>I personally don't like those "snooty" high enders either, the attitude is tedious and rude at best. Some of them can be downright mean, almost "in your face" about how good they are and blah, blah, blah. Like wow, the rest of us would probably be be that good too, &nbsp;if we where on 24/7 like they were.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>That doesn't mean all high end raiders are like that, some are very nice, professional even.</DIV><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<DIV></DIV>
<P><FONT color=#ff0000>Those are the ones i mock in general and try to drive to insanity every chance i get. Most of the high end guilds expect their members to act human. If they dont then peer pressure will help them to see the light. </FONT></P>
<P><FONT color=#ff0000>If nothing else watching the general flow by with people flaming the "uber" is always fun and entertaining. Best of all of course is to play the meta game on them since they may have 20k and 2500 ac but it doesnt mean anything if they have a 3 day suspension for swearing in public chat <img src='/i/smilies/16x16_smiley-happy.gif' width=16 height=16 border=0></FONT></P>	
