		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Battleblade-Xegony wrote:<BR>On some servers people want to raid but are not members of big guilds or even necessarily members of guilds at all. The BIG secret? Public raiding.<BR><BR>Nothing whatsoever prevents people from raiding except their own personal initiative. Don't want to leave your small family guild, need to raid at 10AM Eastern Standard Time on Saturday?? You CAN in fact have it your way. Nothing is stopping anyone except a willingness to do the legwork.<BR><BR>Unable to get flagged to do VT? Unable to ally with another guild to do a raid? Unable to organize a pickup raid on your server? No pain/no gain. Public raids have done PoTime, Anguish, and a variety of targets. Wanting to raid is not the test. The test is wanting to raid enough to do something about it. Others have, and they have reaped the rewards.<BR><BR>On E'ci, I attended countless numbers of PoHate raids - public, signup PoHate raids. 60+ person non-guild raids. Don't claim because you or the players on your server lack the initiative to do the same that raids should be designed for 24 players - not if as has been claimed a LOT of casuals want to raid. Sign them up for a public raid if there are as many as you claim. Others have.<BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Ah yes the infamous pickup raids.&nbsp; Here's the problem, I tried that very method.&nbsp; There is a commonly known open channel on Fennin that has been there for years.&nbsp; I've attended raids announced in that channel, and every one of them was an utter failure.&nbsp; Now I don't mean they failed to take out the final boss, I mean they failed to draw enough of a force to even attempt the raid.&nbsp; Only once did they have a sufficient force to do the walk in PoI to get to the factory and even then it was 3 hours before we got to the NPC we were supposed to protect.&nbsp; I'm sorry but pickup raiding is not the answer to oversized raiding.&nbsp; Look at it this way, which is more enjoyable, more organized and more efficient, a group of close friends and guildies or a random pickup group slapped together with LFG and people you don't know.&nbsp; The answer is obviously the former for the most part so the same is true for raiding.&nbsp; I don't by the no pain no gain idea here, because frankly any raiding I have done in pick up raids has been ALL pain and NO gain.&nbsp; Of late when I sign into that open channel there is maybe 24 people in there and most have the maturity of a 6 year old and are spending all their time flaming each other, talking trash, or linking uberitem_001 someone linked to them.&nbsp; So no pickup raids aren't going to cut it.&nbsp; The only true choices these days are join an established guild that fields a 54 force, attempt to build one from the ground up (as diffult as assembling a quality force in a pickup raid), or saying screw it and not raiding at all, and eventually just leaving as I have watched many people do.&nbsp; You see I've seen lots of people over the years that wanted to raid.&nbsp; They tried pickups to no avail.&nbsp; They tried guilds but only a select few made it that way, the rest eventually gave up on the game entirely.&nbsp; No they didn't go to one of the other games, they just flat quit gaming, because they pretty much expect the same elsewhere.&nbsp;&nbsp; No one has really shown me a reason that raiding should require as many people as it does.&nbsp; At one time when restrictions couldn't be placed on raids sure it made sense to overpower mobs to restrict the raid, but that is no longer true.&nbsp; Today you can limit raid size and tune the targets to that size.&nbsp; </P>
<P>Now maybe gear and progress have run too far ahead of that technology, to where changing it now would mean several expansions of gimp raid content, but then again, maybe not.&nbsp; They have the ability to tune this stuff so it would be challenging for an anquish geared force of 24.&nbsp; It seems to me that change is the bad word here, but frankly it would do the game a world of good imo.&nbsp; I truely think alot of people would stop looking so closely at the stat differences on gear, and actually spend their time progressing more.&nbsp; Can anyone give a good reason for the 54 person force as being "ideal" other than "it is the way we did it"?<BR></P>
<DIV></DIV>
