<HR>
Lunrak wrote:<BR><BR>
<P>And I am not saying&nbsp;raiders have no lives, I'm saying some people, to become raiders would have to give up all semblance of a life in order to do it, and that is an unjust price to pay to satisfy the hardcore who scream for more effort by those players.</P>
<P><FONT color=#ff0000>No, it's the perfect thing for them to scream about.&nbsp; If someone wants to make the game their only form of entertainment and wants to focus so heavily on the game, they deserve their rewards.&nbsp; You're basically saying that it's unfair that people with more time and spend more time playing doing much more challenging content have better rewards... I don't see anything 'unfair' about it until you start complaining that YOU can't do it.&nbsp; I don't see you complaining about it being so unfair that some people have more time to level than others... why is it only an issue when gear/progression come into play.</FONT></P>
<P>You do have to put effort forth, I totally agree, but why does that effort have to come in the form of finding 53 friends when challenging, fun, rewarding raids can be designed around smaller forces?&nbsp; There is no longer a logical reason to force guilds to the sizes they are for raiding when every encounter can now be instanced, and tuned for a max number of players and a set of gear.&nbsp; The only reason it continues is because it has always been that way.&nbsp; That is typically a horrid reason to keep doing something.&nbsp; </P>
<P><FONT color=#ff0000>And what about the people that WANT 50+ person raids... the people that like not having to be in the SAME&nbsp;main tank rotation day after day... the people that like organizing a HUGE force to take down a large target.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT color=#ff0000>You say that raiders shouldn't be screaming about a problem, yet here you are telling SOE to take out the 54 person raid content!.... there has to be rewards for every type of playstyle,&nbsp;you said it yourself, putting together a 54 person raid is a HUGE and difficult task, and justifiably deserves the best rewards.&nbsp; There are people that enjoy these things, and just because you want the same rewards for organizing only HALF the people, I don't see a plausible reason for tearing down the content and benefits that come w/ guilds that enjoy and DO organize those large scale raids.</FONT>
<HR>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<DIV>You're only contradicting yourself... you're complaining about how hard it is to get, organize, and mobilize 54 people, yet you're complaining that those that DO it are given such great rewards...</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>the gap exists for exactly that reason... time + challenge = rewards.&nbsp; Casual players on average have less time, less organization, and are doing much less challenging content... it would be a slap in the face to anyone who puts in more time, more organization and doing cutting edge content to simply hand out items with very little noticeable upgrade potential.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>If you're so intent on opening up the raiding community to the large number of casual players that are so desperate for successful, efficient raids... why don't YOU start running some efficient raids on your open raid channel?&nbsp; on Drinal, we had one open raiding community actually become a guild, and we get 80+ people on a very successful open raid channel...</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>if your community wants to raid so badly and wants raid style gear... their lack of participation is only hurting themselves... and they'll surely get no pity from me.</DIV>
