<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
The-Fabled-IksarSK-Drinal wrote:<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Lunrak wrote:<BR><BR>
<P>And I am not saying&nbsp;raiders have no lives, I'm saying some people, to become raiders would have to give up all semblance of a life in order to do it, and that is an unjust price to pay to satisfy the hardcore who scream for more effort by those players.</P>
<P><FONT color=#ff0000>No, it's the perfect thing for them to scream about.&nbsp; If someone wants to make the game their only form of entertainment and wants to focus so heavily on the game, they deserve their rewards.&nbsp; You're basically saying that it's unfair that people with more time and spend more time playing doing much more challenging content have better rewards... I don't see anything 'unfair' about it until you start complaining that YOU can't do it.&nbsp; I don't see you complaining about it being so unfair that some people have more time to level than others... why is it only an issue when gear/progression come into play.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT color=#ffff66>Ah so if someone focus 5 hours a day every evening to the game in leiu of most other forms of entertainment, progressing their character they deserver the rewards?&nbsp; Funny that is what I'm saying all along, but unless you raid (which takes place too late for alot of people I know) you don't get those rewards.&nbsp; Not talking about people with more time, talking about people that are able to raid till the wee hours of the morning while others can't.&nbsp; You see even if I only have 1 hour a day to level I can still level, just slower.&nbsp; But if I play 4-5 hours a day (which I do) that doesn't mean I'm going to get any where progression wise, because the raids on my server take place later than I can attend since I would like to keep my job.</FONT></P>
<P>You do have to put effort forth, I totally agree, but why does that effort have to come in the form of finding 53 friends when challenging, fun, rewarding raids can be designed around smaller forces?&nbsp; There is no longer a logical reason to force guilds to the sizes they are for raiding when every encounter can now be instanced, and tuned for a max number of players and a set of gear.&nbsp; The only reason it continues is because it has always been that way.&nbsp; That is typically a horrid reason to keep doing something.&nbsp; </P>
<P><FONT color=#ff0000>And what about the people that WANT 50+ person raids... the people that like not having to be in the SAME&nbsp;main tank rotation day after day... the people that like organizing a HUGE force to take down a large target.</FONT></P>
<P><FONT color=#ffff66>At one point I offered a different alternative, and that is creating content that would scale better with the size of the force.&nbsp; So you would have normal single group content like we do now that rewards accordingly.&nbsp; Raid content tuned for the 24 person raid force and rewards better than single group, but less than 54+ raiding, and then the 54+ raiding that rewards as it already does.&nbsp; Something for everyone.&nbsp; You get the better gear through progressively more effort and challenge.&nbsp; You don't have to change your entire life around the game to do it.&nbsp; What is wrong with that idea?</FONT></P>
<P><FONT color=#ff0000>You say that raiders shouldn't be screaming about a problem, yet here you are telling SOE to take out the 54 person raid content!.... there has to be rewards for every type of playstyle,&nbsp;you said it yourself, putting together a 54 person raid is a HUGE and difficult task, and justifiably deserves the best rewards.&nbsp; There are people that enjoy these things, and just because you want the same rewards for organizing only HALF the people, I don't see a plausible reason for tearing down the content and benefits that come w/ guilds that enjoy and DO organize those large scale raids.</FONT>
<P><FONT color=#ffff66>Again I actually suggested a tier of raiding that falls in-between 54 person raids and single group content.&nbsp; Maybe you missed that post, but I did suggest it.&nbsp; I am not asking for the SAME rewards either, I'm talking rewards that scale better.&nbsp; In fact I have repeatedly stated in this thread that I have NO issues with the difference between single group gear and raid gear.&nbsp; What I am suggesting is one of two solutions, which one is implemented I wouldn't care, but both would be beneficial to the game in the long run.</FONT>
<HR>

<P></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<DIV>You're only contradicting yourself... you're complaining about how hard it is to get, organize, and mobilize 54 people, yet you're complaining that those that DO it are given such great rewards...</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>the gap exists for exactly that reason... time + challenge = rewards.&nbsp; Casual players on average have less time, less organization, and are doing much less challenging content... it would be a slap in the face to anyone who puts in more time, more organization and doing cutting edge content to simply hand out items with very little noticeable upgrade potential.</DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#ffff66>Based on the common definition of "casual" I fall into that category yet I am easily online as often and for as long as any raider.&nbsp; Don't assume that because someone is a non raider they put in less time and effort than a raider it is arrogant.</FONT></DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#ffff66>I am well aware of the challenge, and the effort involved in raiding and I understand it means greater rewards.&nbsp; I am actually suggesting ways for those that currently don't raid to move CLOSER to that type of time and challenge and thereby get closer to but not equal to those rewards.&nbsp; It is a slap in the face that I can spend 5 hours a night in game, but it counts as nothing in the effort department when I want to raid.&nbsp;&nbsp; Isn't it obvious that more people would raid if their were more guilds to join that could raid?&nbsp; And isn't it equally obvious that there would be more guilds to join for raiding if the requirement to raid was not so steep?</FONT></DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#ffff66></FONT>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>If you're so intent on opening up the raiding community to the large number of casual players that are so desperate for successful, efficient raids... why don't YOU start running some efficient raids on your open raid channel?&nbsp; on Drinal, we had one open raiding community actually become a guild, and we get 80+ people on a very successful open raid channel...</DIV>
<DIV><FONT color=#ffff66>Again with who?&nbsp; I stated previously that the open raid channel on Fennin has about 25 people in it at peak hours, and that the majority are of low quality hacks doing nothing but talking trash in an open channel.&nbsp; If I knew 60 people I'd be doing those raids already.&nbsp; You can't find those 60 people because like many others they gave up on the idea of raiding long ago when 72 was the max, and it was just ridiculous to fathom creating a force that size from scratch.&nbsp; I'm not saying raiders in large guilds don't deserve their rewards, I never have. What I am saying though is that should not be the sole way to progress.&nbsp; </FONT></DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>if your community wants to raid so badly and wants raid style gear... their lack of participation is only hurting themselves... and they'll surely get no pity from me.</DIV>
<P><FONT color=#ffff66>No one asked for your pity.&nbsp; Of course no one asked for your approval either.&nbsp; The point is that there is absolutely no reason whatsoever to not create raiding content that caters to a smaller force, for lesser rewards than the 54 person raids get.&nbsp;&nbsp;All you have done is continue to exemplify why the casual v. raider arguements continue, the attitude that the only thing that counts is raiding with 60 some odd people and everything else is without effort, merit or challenge, and therefore deserves nothing but the minimum.&nbsp; That no compromise is acceptable and that it needs to stay as it is, because it would be unfair to 4-5 guilds on a given server, as opposed to the community as a whole.&nbsp; THAT is what bothers me.&nbsp; I am not bothered by the "gear gap" between grouping and raiding at least not to the point that I want group gear that parallels CoA or even GoD raid content. I'm talking about scaleability.&nbsp; If the gear gap is supposed to be 50% then there should be raid content in the middle as well that is 25% behind top gear.&nbsp; It still requires organization, effort and challenge with a smaller force.&nbsp;&nbsp; Can you give one legitimate, logical reason why that is unfair or would trivialize anything raiders have done?&nbsp; God forbid we add another path to progression outside of what raiders consider the holy grail of play styles.</FONT>
<HR>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<DIV></DIV>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
