		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV>Aye, there is ton's of stuff that can be done with 3 or less groups. Heck, stuff that used to take full raids can be done by one group ... now, yes. We understand that part. What I'm looking for is a way to progress though, actual progression into the next phase, farming zone, etc. It might be way too much for SOE to do, like Ice suggested, but would it be something that would make Raider's (Hardcore types) uncomfortable, or would it actually help in other ways, such as backflagging. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Let's look at guild A, A = Family guild. They have done everything family guilds are known for, over and over. Endless epic hunts, OS/Hs, even ST keys. Endless quests, over and over they have done them and are wanting to move forward now. They want to keep it a close family (Lots like this in game by the way), but want to move forward, meaning progress. If content had a 24 person raid route for progression, it would make it at least a possibility to try. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>One thing people might not realise, is that not all family guilds are actually small. They can have over 300 people in them, but still appear to be small. Some people in family guild's only log on once a week, or only during the weekend, or maybe only at lunch time for an hour, etc. Even with 300+ members, you might only see a dozen on at any given time. Peak times might yeild 20 or more people, but generally, it's a much smaller number vs. membership. In a Raid guild, 75% or more log on right at raid time, making that /who all 'guild too many to count. Yet they might have the same amount of people in their guild. This is active membership, and inactive membership in alot of people eye's, but realistically, just like thier is many tier's of progression, there is many levels of activity. A member is still active, even if they only log in once a week, or once a month. IT's just not as drastic as a daily log in. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>All in all, everyone posting is bringing thoughts to the boards because they see a situation in thier own game play, or their own guild's game play, and are trying to come here for help. Ice's post was posted as a helpfull bit of advice. Frodlin's post was very informative, but I wonder if he get's the point about progression. Either way, it was very informative (and I'm going to copy and paste for information reason's to my own guild's websight). Sometimes I wonder about your posts Fabled. At times they are very considerate and helpfull, sometimes even benificial. But in here you seem downright annoying at times. Your saying, bassically, play the game the way it is or quit. People post from real concerns, and weather or not YOU Feel they have a legitimate concern, isn't helping when you say exactly the same thing everytime but word it slightly different. I'm one of them people that looks at the glass and see's it is half full, not half empty. IF I can't see the fullfillment of it, or think it's not worthy of concern, then I just don't comment on it at all. Looking at your posts, you don't think this is a good idea at all, and actually don't want it. If that's what your saying, then that's all we really need to hear. If I ask you for some water, and you say No, that's all that has to be said. You don't have to keep telling me no, I get it.</DIV>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							"One falsehood destroys a thousand truths." "Do not think of yourself higher than you ought to think" "If you are not guilty of the robbery then you should not hold on to the loot!" -NOEL BRYSON, Ph

The wise discuss ideas, the normal discuss events, the ignorant discuss other's.
							</div>
								
